Given a class with a mutable default argument:

class TaskTracker:
    def __init__(self, tasks: list = []):
        self.tasks = tasks

    def add_task(self, task: str) -> None:
        self.tasks.append(task)

    def list_tasks(self) -> list:
        return self.tasks

The mutable default causes unexpected sharing between instances.
Fix it so each instance has its own list.
Do not change the external behavior of any public method.
Do not change the constructor signature.
Existing callers that pass an explicit list must still work.
